{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:26:20.904902+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"issues\":[{\"number\":1,\"title\":\"DSN with mixed-case password fails to authenticate (works in psql)\",\"body\":\"Hi — running into something odd. We have a service account whose\\npassword contains uppercase characters and a `+` sign:\\n\\n    Password: Service+Acct.2024\\n\\nConnecting with raw psql works:\\n\\n    $ PGPASSWORD=\\u0026#39;Service+Acct.2024\\u0026#39; psql -h db.internal -U svc_user app_db\\n    # connects fine\\n\\nBut via pgcli using a DSN, it fails with \\u0026#34;password authentication failed\\nfor user svc_user\\u0026#34;:\\n\\n    $ pgcli \\u0026#34;postgresql://svc_user:Service%2BAcct.2024@db.internal/app_db\\u0026#34;\\n\\nI url-encoded the `+` to `%2B` per RFC 3986 (since `+` in query\\nstrings means space). pgcli still reports auth failure. If I drop\\nthe special chars from the password it works.\\n\\nMy read of `pgcli/auth.py` is that pgcli parses the DSN with\\nurllib and passes the unquoted password to psycopg, which itself\\nalso does some decoding — possibly the password is being decoded\\ntwice somewhere and the `+` is being interpreted as a space on the\\npgcli side.\\n\\nIs this a known issue with DSN passwords in pgcli? Should I file\\na PR to switch to `urllib.parse.quote(safe=\\u0026#39;\\u0026#39;)` round-tripping?\\nOr is the recommendation to use `~/.pgpass` for special-char\\npasswords and not put them in the DSN?\\n\\npgcli 4.x, psycopg 3.1, postgres 16, Linux.\\n\\n---\\n\\nUpdate: did a bit more digging on our side. We had a stale\\n`pg_hba.conf` rule on the server (`md5` instead of `scram-sha-256`)\\nthat was rejecting any password longer than ~24 chars before getting\\nto the actual password check. After fixing the auth method on the\\nserver, the original DSN works in pgcli — `+` is being decoded\\ncorrectly.\\n\\nSo this turned out to be a server-side config issue masquerading\\nas a pgcli URL-decoding bug. False alarm, sorry for the noise.\\n\\n(That said, the auth-failed error message in pgcli might be worth\\nmaking more helpful — a generic \\u0026#34;password authentication failed\\u0026#34;\\nhides whether it\\u0026#39;s pgcli-side or server-side. But that\\u0026#39;s a separate\\nissue.)\\n\\nClosing this from my side. Thanks for taking a look!\",\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"user\":{\"login\":\"BruceKZ\"},\"created_at\":\"2026-05-22T11:15:09Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-05-22T11:15:09Z\"}],\"totalCount\":1,\"pageInfo\":{\"hasNextPage\":false,\"hasPreviousPage\":false,\"startCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQxMToxNTowOVrPAAAAAQxZfeY=\",\"endCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQxMToxNTowOVrPAAAAAQxZfeY=\"}}", "id": "lc_2b56f36c-1876-4b7b-a70b-65175d74e789"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "list_issues", "id": "ca4f6482-4539-4900-aa29-74a3204d17a4", "tool_call_id": "call_00_Hcfhew5APxh8w7pjr6nb7323", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
