{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:26:59.877289+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "## Triage Analysis — Issue #1\n\n**Issue:** \"DSN with mixed-case password fails to authenticate (works in psql)\"  \n**Reporter:** BruceKZ  \n**Status:** Still OPEN (no comments, no labels)\n\n### What happened\n\n1. The reporter initially suspected a pgcli bug where a DSN containing a `+` character (URL-encoded as `%2B`) in the password failed authentication.\n2. After deeper investigation, they discovered the real cause was a **server-side PostgreSQL configuration issue** — a stale `pg_hba.conf` entry using `md5` instead of `scram-sha-256`, which rejected passwords longer than ~24 characters.\n3. After fixing the server's auth method, the DSN worked correctly in pgcli (`+` was decoded properly).\n4. The reporter explicitly concluded: *\"So this turned out to be a server-side config issue masquerading as a pgcli URL-decoding bug. False alarm, sorry for the noise. Closing this from my side.\"*\n\n### Recommended action\n\n| Action | Why |\n|--------|-----|\n| **Close as \"completed\"** | The issue was a false alarm — the root cause was server-side, not a pgcli bug. The reporter themselves asked to close it. |\n| **Add a label** (e.g., `invalid` or `works-as-expected`) | To indicate the issue is not a valid code defect. |\n| **Comment** | Acknowledge the reporter's follow-up findings and confirm closure. |\n\n### Limitation encountered\n\nThe current API token does **not** have write permissions on this repository (all PATCH/POST attempts returned 403). I was unable to close the issue, add a comment, or apply labels programmatically. \n\n**If you have appropriate permissions, please close issue #1 as completed** — the reporter already identified and resolved the issue on their end (server config fix) and explicitly requested closure.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 470, "prompt_tokens": 